{{Infobox university |name = Windsor University School of Medicine |image_size = 200px |established = 2000 |type = [[Private university|Private]] |president = Dr. Srinivas Gaddam (deceased)<ref>{{cite web|title=SKNVibes {{!}} In Memory: Srinivas Gaddam, MD|url=http://www.sknvibes.com/news/newsdetails.cfm/88021|website=www.sknvibes.com}}</ref> |dean = Dr. Andy Vaithilingham |students = 1,500 (Fall 2011)<ref name="c" /> |city = [[Cayon]], [[Saint Mary Cayon Parish|Saint Mary Cayon]] |country = [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]] |campus = [[Rural]] |website = {{url|http://www.windsor.edu}} |image_name = Windsor University School of Medicine Logo new.png |colors = {{color box|blue}}{{color box|gold}} [[Blue]] and [[Gold (color)|gold]] }}
'''Windsor University School of Medicine''' is a [[private university|private]] [[medical school]] located in [[Cayon]], [[Saint Mary Cayon Parish]], [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]]. Windsor confers upon its graduates the [[Doctor of Medicine]] (MD) degree.<ref name="b">{{cite web|url=https://imed.faimer.org/details.asp?country=661&school=&currpage=1&cname=SAINT+KITTS+AND+NEVIS&city=&region=CA&rname=Central+America%2FCaribbean&mcode=661040&psize=25 |title=FAIMER International Medical Education Directory - School Details |publisher=faimer.org |date= |accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref> The university also has clinical education campuses in [[Carbondale, Illinois]] and [[Houghton Lake, Michigan]]. Administrative offices are located in [[Monee, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://windsor.edu/new_site/contactus.htm |title=Windsor University School of Medicine - Contact Us |publisher=windsor.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref>
== History == [[File:Windsor Campus.jpg|thumb|left|250px|A building on the Windsor University Saint Kitts [[campus]]]] Windsor was founded in December 1998 on [[Grand Turk Island]] in [[Turks and Caicos]] by Dr. Srinivas Gaddam. Instruction began with a class of eight students. In 2000, the university relocated to Bird Rock,{{cn|date=October 2011}} a town in the [[Saint George Basseterre Parish]] in Saint Kitts, with twelve students.<ref name="c">{{cite web|url=http://www.sknvibes.com/news/newsdetails.cfm/44535 |title=Windsor University School of Medicine held its Inaugural Commencement Exercises |publisher=SKNVibes |date=2011-10-04 |accessdate=2011-10-08}}</ref>
In 2004, Windsor acquired the Royal Plaza Inn in Carbondale, Illinois as a site for 5th semester training and announced plans to relocate the Bird Rock campus to the town of Cayon in the [[Saint Mary Cayon Parish]].<ref>{{cite press release |title=Upscale Housing and Tourism Development Initiatives Unveiled for Cayon |url=http://www.cuopm.com/newsitem.asp?articlenumber=5 |publisher=Office of the Prime Minister of St. Kitts & Nevis |date=2004-08-18 |accessdate=2011-08-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Royal Plaza Inn - a med school? |author=Stephen Rickerl |url=http://thesouthern.com/news/local/article_abbdd6c4-2c33-11e0-b392-001cc4c03286.html |newspaper=The Southern |date=2011-01-30 |accessdate=2011-09-07}}</ref> Windsor began construction on the new Cayon campus in 2006.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}} Windsor acquired the Atrium Plaza hotel in Houghton Lake, Michigan and the Sidney Inn in Sidney, Ohio for use as additional 5th semester training sites in 2009 and 2010, respectively.<ref>{{cite news |title=Atrium Plaza site of medical boards study conferences |author=Cheryl Holladay |url=http://www.houghtonlakeresorter.com/news/2009-10-01/front_page/004.html |newspaper=The Houghton Lake Resorter |date=2009-10-01 |accessdate=2011-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Extensive renovations under way at Sidney Inn |author=Tom Barnett |url=http://sidneydailynews.com/main.asp?Search=1&ArticleID=232223&SectionID=4&SubSectionID=13&S=1 |newspaper=Sidney Daily News |date=2011-07-13 |accessdate=2011-09-07}}</ref>
Currently the Windsor campus at Cayon contains six buildings on {{convert|42|acre|km2 sqmi}} of land.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://windsor.edu/new_site/word/student_handbook.pdf |title=Windsor University School of Medicine - Student Academic Policies and Procedures Handbook |publisher=windsor.edu |page=62 |accessdate=2011-09-07}}</ref> The most recent addition, the [[Robert Llewellyn Bradshaw]] building, was completed in September 2010, at which time the enrollment was approximately 1,100 students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sknvibes.com/news/newsdetails.cfm/15176 |title=Medical University names new classroom building in honour of Sir Robert Llewellyn Bradshaw |publisher=SKNVibes |date=2010-09-18 |accessdate=2011-08-11}}</ref> Also in September 2010, Windsor announced plans for further expansion with new laboratories and a 1500 seat auditorium.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestkittsnevisobserver.com/2010/09/24/windsor-expansion.html |title=Windsor University Plans to Expand |newspaper=The St. Kitts-Nevis Observer |date=2010-09-24 |accessdate=2011-08-10}}</ref> The university enrollment was approximately 1,500 students as of October 2011.<ref name="c" /> {{clear}}
== Curriculum == [[File:Windsor Administration Building.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Library and administration building]] The MD program at Windsor is a 10 semester course of study that consists of three semesters per calendar year. Semesters 1-4 are [[Medicine#Basic_sciences|basic sciences]] semesters that are completed at the university's Saint Kitts campus. Semester 5 (Introduction to Clinical Medicine) is completed either at the Saint Kitts campus or at one of the university's three clinical education campuses in the [[United States]]. Semesters 6-10 consist of 72 weeks of [[clerkship (medicine)|clinical clerkships]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.windsor.edu/new_site/curriculum.htm |title=Windsor University School of Medicine - Curriculum |publisher=windsor.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref> that are completed at either Joseph Nathaniel France General Hospital in Saint Kitts or hospitals in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.windsor.edu/new_site/clinicalrotation.html |title=Windsor University School of Medicine - Clinical Rotations |publisher=windsor.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref>
Windsor also offers a 3 semester [[pre-medical]] program for high school graduates who have not completed the necessary prerequisites for the MD program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.windsor.edu/new_site/premed-md.htm |title=Windsor University School of Medicine - Premed/MD Program |publisher=windsor.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-09-04}}</ref> {{clear}}
== Accreditation and recognition == Windsor University School of Medicine is chartered in Saint Kitts and [[Educational accreditation|accredited]] by the Accreditation Board of Saint Kitts and Nevis,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ab.gov.kn/?q=node/26 |title=Accredited Institutions - St. Kitts & Nevis Accreditation Board |publisher=gov.kn |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref> a recognized accrediting agency listed in the [[Foundation for Advancement of International Medical Education and Research|FAIMER]] Directory of Organizations that Recognize/Accredit Medical Schools (DORA).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.faimer.org/resources/dora/saintkittsnevis.html |title=FAIMER - Directory of Organizations that Recognize/Accredit Medical Schools - Saint Kitts and Nevis |publisher=faimer.org |accessdate=2011-09-05}}</ref> The university is listed in the [[World Directory of Medical Schools]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://search.wdoms.org/home/SchoolDetail/F0001715|title=School Detail|website=search.wdoms.org|access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref> but was denied accreditation by the [[Caribbean Accreditation Authority for Education in Medicine and other Health Professions|CAAM-HP]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caam-hp.org/programs|title=Caribbean Accreditation Authority for Education in Medicine and Other Health Professions |website=www.caam-hp.org|access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref>
== Student life == Several student organizations exist at Windsor. These include, but are not limited to: * [[American Medical Student Association]] (AMSA)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amsa.org/AMSA/Homepage/MemberCenter/Intl/IntlChapters.aspx |title=AMSA International Medical Schools |publisher=amsa.org |date= |accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref> * [[Student Government]]<ref name="a">{{cite web|url=http://www.sknvibes.com/news/newsdetails.cfm/15025 |title=A place for second chances – Windsor University School of Medicine |publisher=SKNVibes |date=2010-08-26 |accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref> * Students for Health, a volunteer community service organization.<ref name="a" /> * Eye On You Foundation, formed to "cater for and improve the quality of life for the elderly."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sknvibes.com/news/newsdetails.cfm/16814 |title=Windsor University students spread love at Cardin Home |publisher=SKNVibes |date=2011-02-15 |accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref> * Muslim Students Association<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sknvibes.com/news/newsdetails.cfm/13428 |title=Windsor University donates to Haitian earthquake relief |publisher=SKNVibes |date=2010-03-09 |accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref>
